Hostname word lists
====================

These files provide the word lists for the "%v" (adverb), "%a" (adjective) and
"%n" (noun) wildcards understood by /etc/hostname (see hostname(5)). A template
such as:

    %a-%n          ->  happy-octopus
    %v-%a-%n-????  ->  wildly-happy-octopus-92a9

is expanded deterministically from the machine ID, so a given machine always
gets the same name.

Files
-----

Each file holds one word per line. Empty lines and lines starting with "#" are
ignored. Each word must be a valid single hostname label (lowercase letters,
digits, hyphens). Invalid entries are skipped. The list is loaded as a whole
from the highest-priority directory that provides it (/etc wins over /run wins
over /usr/lib); lists are not merged across directories.

Search path (highest priority first):

    /etc/systemd/hostname-words/{adverbs,adjectives,nouns}
    /run/systemd/hostname-words/...
    /usr/local/lib/systemd/hostname-words/...
    /usr/lib/systemd/hostname-words/...

Caveats
-------

One word per class is picked once on the first boot and persisted (in
/var/lib/systemd/hostname-words-picked), so once a machine has been given a
name, later changes to these lists do not change it. (Before that first pick,
or if /var/ is reset, the name is derived live from the current lists.) If a
referenced list is missing the name is treated as invalid and the built-in
fallback hostname is used.

Origin
------

These are the "small" word lists taken from the petname project
(https://github.com/dustinkirkland/petname), distributed under the Apache
License 2.0. Distributions are encouraged to ship larger lists (petname also
provides "medium" and "large") for a bigger name space.
